@chapter Customizing Indentation
@ifinfo

@end ifinfo
@cindex semantics
@cindex langelem
Unlike BOCM and c++-mode, indentation customization in CC-Mode is much
more intuitive and flexible.  This is because indentation for a
particular line is split into two distinct steps.  First, CC-Mode tries
to determine the @dfn{semantics} of the line.  In other words, what
semantic role in the source code does the line play?  Is it a label?  Is
it the first statement in a block?  CC-Mode will first analyze the line,
generating a list of language elements (abbreviated here as
@dfn{langelems}) describing the semantics of the line.

@vindex{c-offsets-alist}
@vindex{c-basic-offset}
After the semantic list is generated, CC-Mode calculates the indentation
offset of the line by added up the individual offset values for each
langelem on the list.  The association list @var{c-offsets-alist}
contains a customizable list associating langelems with offsets.  These
offsets are usually described in terms of a basic indentation value, as
described in the variable @var{c-basic-offset}.
